# Security & Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)

## Rule
Every newly exposed endpoint or resource mutation must explicitly declare an authentication and authorization layer.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Unless a route is explicitly documented as public (e.g. via a clear comment or a `@Public()` decorator), every handler must enforce identity verification using Guards, e.g.:
  ```typescript
  @UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard)
  @Roles(Role.User)
  ```
- The handler (or the service it delegates to) must implement strict **resource-ownership validation**: the authenticated principal (`req.user.id` / JWT subject) must be checked against the target wallet, account, or resource being read or modified. Authorization must not stop at "is this user logged in" — it must confirm "does this user own/control this specific resource."
- Endpoints that mutate balances, escrow state, or any P2P transaction record require both authentication *and* ownership checks; authentication alone is insufficient.

## What to flag in review
- New `@Controller`/`@Resolver` handlers without `@UseGuards(...)` and no explicit `@Public()` marker or comment justifying public access.
- Guards present but ownership not verified — e.g. a `PATCH /wallets/:id` handler that checks the JWT is valid but never confirms `req.user.id === wallet.ownerId`.
- Roles applied too broadly (e.g. `@Roles(Role.User)` on an admin-only operation, or missing `@Roles` entirely on sensitive mutations).
- Authorization logic duplicated ad-hoc per handler instead of centralized in a Guard or a reusable ownership-check utility/service method.

## Example

```typescript
// ❌ Bad — no guard, no ownership check
@Patch('wallets/:id')
async updateWallet(@Param('id') id: string, @Body() dto: UpdateWalletDto) {
  return this.walletsService.update(id, dto);
}

// ✅ Good — guarded, role-checked, ownership-verified
@UseGuards(JwtAuthGuard, RolesGuard)
@Roles(Role.User)
@Patch('wallets/:id')
async updateWallet(
  @Param('id') id: string,
  @Body() dto: UpdateWalletDto,
  @CurrentUser() user: AuthUser,
) {
  return this.walletsService.updateOwned(id, dto, user.id); // service enforces ownership
}
```
